# Heat Manager — Claude/Cursor Ruleset
# Based on: Home Assistant Integration Quality Scale (2026)
# Target tier: Gold → Platinum
# Project: custom_components/heat_manager
# Author: @kingpainter | International release | English first

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 1. PROJECT IDENTITY & LANGUAGE
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

- All code, comments, docstrings, commit messages, PR descriptions, and
  GitHub issues are written in English. No exceptions.
- Danish is only permitted inside translation files:
    custom_components/heat_manager/translations/da.json
- The primary translation file is English (en.json). Danish (da.json) is
  maintained in parallel. Every new string added to en.json must have a
  corresponding entry in da.json in the same commit.

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 2. VERSION CONTROL — STRICT SEMVER
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

- Version follows Semantic Versioning: MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH
    MAJOR — breaking change to config entry schema or behaviour
    MINOR — new feature, new entity, new service, backwards compatible
    PATCH — bug fix, translation update, documentation update
- Version is declared in ONE place only: manifest.json ("version" key).
  All other references (const.py VERSION, README badges) read from it or
  are updated in the same commit.
- Never commit a version bump without a matching CHANGELOG.md entry.
- Never skip a version number.

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 3. GIT COMMIT CONVENTIONS
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# Format: <type>(<scope>): <short description>
# Max 72 characters on the first line. Body is optional, separated by blank line.

# Types:
#   feat      New feature or entity
#   fix       Bug fix (reference bug number if known: "fix(window): B3 - ...")
#   docs      README, CHANGELOG, docstrings only — no code change
#   test      Adding or updating tests only
#   refactor  Code change that neither fixes a bug nor adds a feature
#   chore     Manifest, requirements, version bump, CI config
#   trans     Translation strings only (en.json / da.json)
#   style     Formatting, whitespace — no logic change (ruff format)

# Scopes (use the module name):
#   controller, presence, window, preheat, season, waste, coordinator,
#   config_flow, entities, frontend, tests, docs, ci

# Examples:
#   feat(controller): add ON/PAUSE/OFF state machine with guard decorator
#   fix(window): B3 - restore schedule only if presence active on close
#   fix(window): B1 - remove leading dot from lukas_vindue_contact entity
#   docs(readme): add installation instructions and HACS badge
#   chore(manifest): bump version 0.1.0 → 0.1.1
#   test(controller): add 13 unit tests for auto-off and guard decorator
#   trans(da): add missing strings for controller_state select entity

# Rules:
# - Imperative mood: "add", "fix", "remove" — NOT "added", "fixes", "removed"
# - No period at the end of the subject line
# - Reference issue numbers in body: "Closes #12" or "Related to #8"
# - One logical change per commit — do not bundle unrelated changes
# - Never commit directly to main. Always use a feature branch.

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 4. BRANCHING STRATEGY
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# main          — always release-ready. Tagged with version on every merge.
# dev           — integration branch. All features merge here first.
# feature/<name> — individual feature branches off dev
# fix/<name>    — bug fix branches off dev (or main for hotfixes)
# docs/<name>   — documentation-only changes

# Branch naming examples:
#   feature/preheat-engine
#   feature/lovelace-card
#   fix/b1-lukas-window-typo
#   fix/b3-window-close-presence-check
#   docs/readme-hacs-install

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 5. FILE & CODE STRUCTURE
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

- All integration files live under custom_components/heat_manager/
- All logic that does NOT depend on homeassistant.* lives in engine/:
    engine/controller.py     — ON/PAUSE/OFF state machine
    engine/presence_engine.py
    engine/window_engine.py
    engine/preheat_engine.py
    engine/season_engine.py
    engine/waste_calculator.py
  Engine files must be importable and testable without a running HA instance.
- Platform files (sensor.py, binary_sensor.py, select.py, switch.py) contain
  only entity class definitions and async_setup_entry. No logic.
- coordinator.py is the single source of truth for shared state. It owns
  the DataUpdateCoordinator and instantiates all engines.
- const.py is the single source of truth for all constants. No magic
  strings anywhere else in the codebase.
- No circular imports. Dependency direction: platforms → coordinator → engines → const.

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 6. HOME ASSISTANT QUALITY SCALE — BRONZE (REQUIRED)
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# All Bronze rules must be satisfied before any release.

- config-flow:
    Integration must be set up exclusively through the UI config flow.
    No YAML setup. config_flow.py must implement async_step_user.

- config-flow-test-coverage:
    tests/components/heat_manager/test_config_flow.py must cover all steps
    and all error paths. Run: pytest tests/ --cov=custom_components/heat_manager

- unique-config-entry:
    async_step_user must call self._async_abort_if_unique_id_configured()
    after setting a stable unique ID. Only one Heat Manager instance allowed.

- entity-unique-id:
    Every entity must have a unique_id. Format:
    f"{entry.entry_id}_{entity_suffix}"  e.g. "abc123_kitchen_state"

- has-entity-name:
    Every entity class must set: has_entity_name = True
    Entity names come from strings.json translations, not hardcoded strings.

- runtime-data:
    The coordinator is stored in entry.runtime_data, not hass.data[DOMAIN].
    Access pattern: coordinator = entry.runtime_data

- action-setup:
    All services (heat_manager.pause, heat_manager.resume, etc.) are
    registered in async_setup_entry in __init__.py, not in async_setup.

- test-before-configure:
    Config flow validates that provided entity IDs exist in HA state machine
    before creating the entry. Returns errors dict on failure.

- test-before-setup:
    async_setup_entry raises ConfigEntryNotReady if coordinator first
    refresh fails (e.g. climate entities unavailable at startup).

- entity-event-setup:
    State change listeners are registered in async_added_to_hass(),
    not in __init__. They are removed in async_will_remove_from_hass().

- common-modules:
    - coordinator.py — coordinator and shared data
    - const.py       — all constants
    - engine/        — all reusable logic

- appropriate-polling:
    SCAN_INTERVAL = timedelta(seconds=60) set in coordinator.py.
    Justified: local state polling only, no external API calls.

- dependency-transparency:
    requirements = [] in manifest.json (no external libraries).
    All HA built-ins used via homeassistant.* imports only.

- brands:
    custom_components/heat_manager/brands/ contains:
      icon.png (256x256), icon@2x.png (512x512)
    These are required for HACS display.

- docs-*:
    README.md must include:
      - High-level description (what it does, why it exists)
      - Step-by-step installation (HACS + manual)
      - All configuration options with types and defaults
      - All service actions with parameters
      - Removal instructions

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 7. HOME ASSISTANT QUALITY SCALE — SILVER (TARGET)
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

- action-exceptions:
    Service handlers raise ServiceValidationError (not generic Exception)
    with a translatable message key. Never silently swallow errors.

- config-entry-unloading:
    async_unload_entry must unload all platforms and cancel all listeners.
    Test: entry can be loaded, unloaded, and reloaded without side effects.

- entity-unavailable:
    If a climate entity goes unavailable (state == "unavailable"), mark the
    corresponding Heat Manager sensor as unavailable too. Do not serve
    stale data.

- integration-owner:
    codeowners = ["@kingpainter"] in manifest.json. Always kept current.

- log-when-unavailable:
    When a climate entity becomes unavailable, log once at WARNING level.
    When it recovers, log once at INFO level. No repeated spam.

- parallel-updates:
    Set PARALLEL_UPDATES = 1 in each platform file (sensor.py etc.).
    All updates go through the coordinator — no direct parallel polling.

- test-coverage:
    Target: >95% line coverage across all engine/ and platform files.
    Measured with: pytest --cov=custom_components/heat_manager --cov-report=term-missing

- reauthentication-flow:
    N/A for this integration (no authentication). Document as exempt
    in quality_scale.yaml with comment: "No authentication required."

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 8. HOME ASSISTANT QUALITY SCALE — GOLD (ASPIRATIONAL)
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

- entity-translations:
    All entity names defined in strings.json and translations/*.json.
    No hardcoded display names in Python code.

- entity-device-class:
    Use device classes wherever HA provides one:
      sensor.energy_wasted_today → SensorDeviceClass.ENERGY
      sensor.efficiency_score    → SensorDeviceClass.POWER_FACTOR (or None)
      binary_sensor.any_window_open → BinarySensorDeviceClass.WINDOW
      binary_sensor.heating_wasted  → BinarySensorDeviceClass.HEAT

- entity-category:
    Diagnostic sensors (pause_remaining, efficiency_score) →
      EntityCategory.DIAGNOSTIC
    Config switches (room overrides) →
      EntityCategory.CONFIG

- diagnostics:
    Implement async_get_config_entry_diagnostics() in diagnostics.py.
    Returns sanitized snapshot of all room states, controller state,
    season mode, and config (no PII, no entity IDs redacted).

- reconfiguration-flow:
    Options flow allows editing global settings and notification prefs
    post-setup. Already implemented via HeatManagerOptionsFlow.

- repair-issues:
    If a configured climate entity is not found at startup, raise a
    RepairIssue with a link to reconfigure, rather than silently failing.

- docs-use-cases:
    README includes 3+ real-world automation examples using Heat Manager
    services (e.g. voice command to pause, dashboard button to force heat).

- docs-troubleshooting:
    README includes a Troubleshooting section covering:
      - "Heating not turning on after arriving home"
      - "Controller auto-turned off unexpectedly"
      - "Entities not showing in HA"
      - How to enable debug logging for the integration

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 9. CODE QUALITY STANDARDS
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

- Formatter: ruff format (not black). Run before every commit.
- Linter: ruff check with HA's ruleset. Zero warnings allowed.
- Type annotations: all function signatures must be fully typed.
  Return type None must be explicit. No bare "-> None" missing.
- from __future__ import annotations at the top of every Python file.
- No bare except: clauses. Always catch specific exception types.
- No mutable default arguments in function signatures.
- _LOGGER = logging.getLogger(__name__) in every module that logs.
- Use f-strings for all string formatting (not % or .format()).
- Maximum line length: 88 characters (ruff default).
- All async functions that call hass.services.async_call use blocking=True
  unless there is a documented reason not to.

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 10. TESTING RULES
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

- Every engine file has a corresponding test file:
    engine/controller.py       → tests/.../test_controller_engine.py
    engine/presence_engine.py  → tests/.../test_presence_engine.py
    engine/window_engine.py    → tests/.../test_window_engine.py
    engine/preheat_engine.py   → tests/.../test_preheat_engine.py
    engine/waste_calculator.py → tests/.../test_waste_calculator.py
- Every bug fix gets a regression test named test_bug_<BN>_<description>
  e.g. test_bug_b1_lukas_window_never_shown()
- Every new service gets at least one happy-path and one error-path test.
- Tests use pytest-asyncio. All async tests decorated @pytest.mark.asyncio.
- Tests use MagicMock / AsyncMock for HA dependencies. Never import
  real HA core in engine tests.
- Do not test implementation details — test observable behaviour.
- Tests must be runnable offline with no HA instance.

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 11. CHANGELOG RULES
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# CHANGELOG.md follows Keep a Changelog format: https://keepachangelog.com
# Every version has exactly these sections (omit empty ones):
#   ### Added
#   ### Changed
#   ### Fixed
#   ### Removed
#   ### Security

# Rules:
# - [Unreleased] section at the top always exists.
# - On release: rename [Unreleased] to [X.Y.Z] - YYYY-MM-DD, add new [Unreleased].
# - Every bug fix references its bug ID: "Fixed B1 - lukas_vindue typo"
# - Every entry is a complete sentence ending with a period.
# - Link version numbers to GitHub compare URLs.

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 12. README RULES
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# README.md must always contain (in order):
#   1. Title + one-line description
#   2. Badges: version, HA min version, HACS, license
#   3. What it does (non-technical, 2-3 paragraphs)
#   4. Features list
#   5. Requirements (HA version, entity types needed)
#   6. Installation (HACS — preferred, Manual — fallback)
#   7. Configuration (all options, types, defaults)
#   8. Services reference (all 4 services with parameters)
#   9. Entities reference (all auto-created entities)
#  10. Lovelace card usage
#  11. Automation examples (3+ real examples)
#  12. Troubleshooting
#  13. Known limitations
#  14. Changelog link
#  15. License

# README is always in English. A separate README_da.md may exist but is
# never the primary file.

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 13. QUALITY_SCALE.YAML
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

# quality_scale.yaml in custom_components/heat_manager/ tracks rule status.
# Valid statuses: done | todo | exempt
# Every rule must have an entry. Exempt rules require a comment explaining why.
# This file is updated in the same commit as the implementing code.

# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 14. WHAT CLAUDE MUST NEVER DO
# ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

- Never use hass.data[DOMAIN] to store the coordinator. Use runtime_data.
- Never hardcode entity IDs in engine files. They come from config entry data.
- Never write Danish in Python files, commit messages, or issue titles.
- Never bump the version without updating CHANGELOG.md in the same commit.
- Never add a new constant to a platform file. Add it to const.py.
- Never write logic in a platform file. Logic belongs in engine/.
- Never use time.sleep() or blocking I/O. Everything is async.
- Never catch Exception broadly. Always catch the specific type.
- Never commit with failing tests.
- Never merge to main without a version bump and CHANGELOG entry.
- Never write a test that requires a live HA instance.
- Never add a TODO comment without a GitHub issue number referencing it.
